1. Core Principles

This framework is built on five universal principles:

Human dignity and individual rights and basic needs

Democratic participation and subsidiarity (decisions made at the
lowest competent level)

Environmental stewardship and sustainability

Equity and access to opportunity

Peaceful coexistence and conflict resolution

2. Three-Tiered Structure2.1. Global Level: Earth Assembly

Institution: United Earth Assembly (UEA)

Representation: Democratically elected representatives by global
population (proportional), plus regional and indigenous
representatives.

Functions:

Enforce basic human rights globally

Address existential threats: climate change, pandemics, nuclear
disarmament

Regulate planetary commons: oceans, atmosphere, space

Coordinate science, emergency response, and global research

Set global ethical standards (e.g., AI, biotech)

2.2. Regional Level: Continental Federations

Examples: African Federation, European Federation, Asian-Pacific
Confederation, etc.

Functions:

Coordinate regional development, infrastructure, migration

Harmonize trade and environmental policies

Represent cultural and economic clusters within the UEA

2.3. Local/National Level: Sovereign Local Governments

Preserve: Language, religion, culture, legal traditions

Functions:

Self-determination within a universal rights framework

Education, health, justice systems

Regional adaptation of global policies

3. Rights & Responsibilities Charter (Global Constitution)

Modeled After: Universal Declaration of Human Rights + Planetary
Boundaries framework

Enshrines:

Right to life, expression, movement, education

Protection of indigenous cultures and minority rights

Right to a clean and safe environment

Duty to future generations

4. Enforcement & Legal System

Global Court of Humanity & Nature

Adjudicates crimes against humanity, ecocide, corruption

Transnational Civil Service

Peacekeepers, environmental monitors, scientific advisors

Ethical Oversight Council

Reviews emerging technologies and moral dilemmas

5. Global Economy & Resource Equity

Planetary Resource Dividend (PRD):

A basic income or service guarantee funded by taxing use of
shared global resources (e.g., carbon, data, deep-sea mining)

Progressive Taxation on Excess Accumulation

Address wealth inequality on a planetary scale

Open Innovation and Knowledge Commons

Education and key technologies open to all

6. Participatory Mechanisms

Global Referenda: Citizens vote directly on key global issues

Deliberative Assemblies: Citizens’ juries and panels to guide
decision-making

Transparency & Digital Governance Tools: Open-source audits,
real-time public dashboards, decentralized voting

Challenges & Caveats

Requires a massive cultural shift and redefinition of
sovereignty

Likely to face elite resistance and geopolitical rivalry

Implementation would be gradual and adaptive, likely beginning
through enhanced versions of current institutions (e.g., UN
reform, regional unions)

A Realistic Path Forward

Reform Existing Bodies (e.g. democratize the UN)

Strengthen Regional Federations (like the EU, AU)

Build Shared Norms via education, media, and civil society

Create Pilot Projects for global citizen assemblies

Establish Emergency Governance Mechanisms for global crises

